posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>69273572
3x12, you do 12 reps, put the weight down then rest for let's say 2 minutes. That's one set. Then you pick up the weight again and do another 12 reps, rest and that'll be 2 sets. You do them one after the other.
There are other types of sets like, drop sets where you do a set, reduce the weight then do another set. There is superset where you do one set of an exercise followed by a set of a different exercise that compliment it (eg. dips followed by pullups)

>>69269330
Space meals out, and start early. How much you can eat isn't actually limited by daily caloric intake. It's generally just by stomach capacity. You can desensitize to satiety by eating more frequently and in larger volumes. Eat breakfast about as soon as you can, and pile it on, then, when you're not full any more, eat again.

My general daily diet is

Wake up (9 am) - Granola bar with daily supplements & water

30 - 40 minutes later
Make breakfast. 4-6 oz of pork, a slice of toast, fried in butter or lard, 2eggs + a spot of milk in an omelette, also fried in butter or lard, ~1/8 cup of yogurt, and a 12 oz mug of tea.

3-4 hours later, I have a 24oz protein shake

4-5 hours later, I'll have dinner.
Dinner is usually varied, but I definitely enjoy having mostly carbs, since for my fitness goals the shake and breakfast cover most of my protein needs. Dishes like Shepherd's pie, stir fry, lasagna, or chili. Sometimes I'll go low effort with ramen and a couple eggs.

I keep a couple tubs of ice cream handy if I ever feel like I've under eaten for the day.

The number one key I feel to my progress has been getting enough sleep, and making a habit of eating a big breakfast.

I have dyspraxia and was always shit at sports, but I found I could hold my own in BJJ. It's relatively slow paced, so my poor reaction times aren't a hindrance, there are no strikes incoming that require hand-eye coordination to block, and it's mostly on the ground so my poor balance doesn't hold me back much either. posts.name: Anonymous

>>69271762
>Also pretty easy, just make a conscious effort to take up as much space with your body as possible - roll your shoulders back, puff your chest out a bit and hold your head up high
Also fix any APT. This is massively overlooked.
>good hair
This is pretty simple. Figure out your face shape (round, square, heart, etc. Use google), figure out your hair texture (thin vs thick, straight, wavy or curly) then search for hair using those terms and whatever length you want. Find a few similar example pics of front and side and take it to a salon (not a barber shop unless they are more "upscale"). If the look works for you, get it maintained every 4-6 weeks.
>good fashion sense
>good glasses
These basically are the same thing. Fashion is easy -- get some staples and make sure they fit properly. Not too tight, not too baggy, and the lengths (sleeves and pant legs) are correct. If you find stuff that fits well off the rack, cool, but most won't because it's all mix-match shit from sweatshops. So find stuff that fits mostly well, is made of comfortable materials, and drop a few bucks to get it tailored. Shit that is "fitted" off the rack is rarely so.
Now those are "staple clothes", so shit you can wear to work and maybe to some times going out (i.e., some polo shirts to wear to an outdoor party in summer). But a true sense of fashion is built to your tastes. Your aesthetic is a combination of details of your clothes and accessories, and that can show off some of your personality. It is also reflective of non-clothing things like your hair. Personally, I hold onto some of the wannabe skater days of my youth, so I will roll up to work in business casual (collared shirt, dark wash jeans or dark chinos, and a leather wristband with slightly longer wavy hair). It polarizes some people, but thats kind of the point. Your aesthetic should fit YOU, literally and figuratively, and that will inevitably draw people to or away from you.

Yes. The mind seeks consistency in all things, even that which it creates. The moment something is out of alignment or unexpected, it creates friction in thinking and often activates the sympathetic nervous system (fight-flight response). It's why you should pursue that which you convince yourself is already present -- no, not that you're lean-pilled and jacked, but that you're an active/athletic person who prefers to take care of your health.

However I'll disagree with this partly. You can do everything "right" and still fail. The point is not in analyzing the failure's contributions to the bad shit in your life, but rather to give you that friction in thought mentioned earlier because that will encourage a change. The more frequently you view failure as an opportunity to change for the better, the less impactful failure becomes in the long run. Conversely, you can also use the failure to justify negative changes -- e.g., a lot of binging after getting fired or going through a breakup.

First off, congrats on identifying the problem. That's step 1. You have motivation to solve it so that's step 2. You're already on the path to improving yourself.

Therapy is always valuable if you can access it.

You can start a journal at this moment. Write down what you consider your most important story of the day/week. Read it again a few days later and interpret it. Look for those negative things you want to improve. Don't beat yourself up, this is a self improvement list, not a self hate list. Make a second list of the things that make you proud because only focusing on the negative can be harmful. Repeat. You'll get better and better each time you do it. The end goal is to increase your objectivity and awareness of what your mind is doing. As you keep the journal consistent that objective awareness will start working in real time. Eventually you'll be able to interfere with bad thoughts as they happen.

Always keep in mind that 100% objectivity and awareness is impossible, monks spend their entire life in the pursuit. If you think you've obtained pure objectivity or awareness you have failed and will stop growing. As long as you keep that growth mindset you'll be healthy and continue to learn

If you want a book I found "Emotional Intelligence 2.0" helpful on my journey. They give a lot of practical things to try out and its an easy read. You can ignore the business jargon without issue.

Nutrition pyramid edition

>Who is /fat/ for?
For fatties who are working towards a better physique through meaningful hard-work, strategy, and dedication. This is not QTDDTOT, stick to questions on fat loss. Post height and weight when asking for advice.
Join our Fatty Contest: https://www.fattycontest.com/

>What do I do first?
1. Read https://physiqonomics.com/fat-loss/
2. Calculate your Body Fat Percentage: https://fitness.bizcalcs.com/Calculator.asp?Calc=Body-Fat-Navy
3. Calculate your TDEE: https://www.sailrabbit.com/bmr/
Remember to use bodyfat% and use Katch-McArdle Formula with sedentary settings or your TDEE will be too high.
4. Plan your weight loss: https://www.losertown.org/eats/cal.php
5. Track your nutrition with MyFitnessPal (better for packaged food), Cronometer (better for generic food/macros) or LoseIt (great for both).

>Now what?
Count calories, all of them.
Eat about 500-1000 less calories than your TDEE.
Buy scales, be accurate.
Learn to cook. Try to stick to lean protein and green vegetables.
Eat a lot of protein. 0.72g per lb of goal lean body mass.
Doing cardio, even just walking, will improve your health. There is no such thing as a healthy fat heart, but you can offset the risks.
Lifting weights will keep and gain muscle mass and burn fat much quicker. No lifting results in the body burning away muscle AND fat.
Drink more water.
Read the /fit/ sticky: https://liamrosen.com/fitness.html

>DON'T
Eat refined sugars, they're terrible for you regardless of calories.
Eat processed foods.
Drink your calories (alcohol, soda, starbucks).
Freak out over a weight loss stall. Plateaus can last up to three weeks.
"Reward" yourself. Cheat days cheat only yourself.

>Other resources:
Loose skin, gyno & stretch marks: https://weight-loss-side-effects.netlify.app/
Reddit wiki: https://www.reddit.com/r/loseit/wiki/faq

This gets posted in fast every once in awhile and always gets deboonked.
Glycogen + water is stored in the liver and muscles.

>Total Mass (g): Total: 66448 or 66.4 Kg

Here's a little calculator you can use to estimate how much glycogen and water weight your body can hold.
(15 to 25 g of glycogen) X (4 to 5 g of water) X (Kg of LBM) / 1000

Now lets calculate.

>Lowest and highest estimate for Glycogen + water weight
(15 to 25) X (4 to 5) X 54 kg / 1000 = 3.2 to 6.75 Kg

>Change in Lean+ BMC
54 - 46.9 = 7.1 Kg

>Actual change in Lean+ BMC
7.1 - (6.75 to 3.2) = 0.35 to 3.9 Kg

>Advice for new runners
- Try to keep your cadence high (at or around 180 steps per minute)
- Try to keep your heartrate in Zone1/2 (around an average of 55-65% of your max. heart rate)

All the running programs list dynamic movements
I just work my way up from the ground, or down from the head.

Free easy clean movements, nothing jerky, with core held firm.

ankle rotations. clockwise, counter clockwise. 30 seconds each foot, each direction. (2 minutes)
Hip rotations, open up those hips. both sides, both directions. 30 seconds each leg, each direction (2 minutes)
Free swing legs from the hip. Frontal Plane, (forward backward) and saggital plane (side to side.) (you guessed it 30 seconds each leg, and plane, so 2 minutes)
I can't remember the name of the next thing, but it's basically Push Kick Drills, not fast just ... pick a spot on the wall, lift your foot up, touch that spot, touch it with toes... extend, push lightly off wall. Yeah, look they're just push kick drills, I can't think of another name.
https://youtu.be/ycdzg6aa6-A
1 minute.
then do some hip gyrations, and look, just do some basic fucking dynamic movements, gyrate hips, gently twist back, rotate arms, roll you neck.

then do 20 seconds of little hops in place.
THEN walk for 5 minutes as a brisk pace.

AND Then run 3 miles(5km) or even 6 miles (10 km) what ever your mid distance is, don't push it to the full 10 miles or whatever.

When stop, walk a couple of minutes, and then do all the standard static stretches.

>Why can't I just go out and run for 20 minutes? why is there 20 minutes of warm up cool down and...
BECAUSE the first half of your current runs are going to catch up with you.

The dynamic movements are to warm up, wake up and loosen up the body for short term mobility, so you don't hurt, and don't injure yourself.
The static stretches after wards are to increase range of motion in the long term.

You want strong flexible mobility, not loose and weak.
Hold each static stretch for 30 seconds for 3 reps, three times a week.
There's diminishing returns after 30 seconds.

Okay, oldboy's sprint warmup (mine, there are infinite permutations) for thought. This is for info purposes and has taken over a year to build up to from sessile lardiness...

Gentle walk into easy jog 400m (some sprinters won't jog more than 100m).
Toe walk then heel walk 20m ea.
Marching - high raised knee (hitting the "z" - raised hip, knees & ankles at approx 90 deg), straight backleg, driving arms in synch w/elbows bent.
Gentle skip 50m (like a child but with shoulders broad, sternum forwards and a bit of a swagger).
Switches (hitting the same shape/ posture as the march but with a pause each time knee is at top position LRLRLR etc)
Pedalling (ankle high - paying attention to dorsiflexion and ankle rigidity)
Hamstring sweeps
"Opening and closing the gate".
High knees (see Loren Seagrave stuff on youtube for example)
Leg swings (back to front and side-side)
A-skip 30m x 2.
Pedalling again, mid-shin height.
B-skip 30m x 2. Alternatively (similarly) "whip from the hip" drill (Seagrave again)
Double foot hopping then single foot hops on each side (work up from small number to start)
Gentle stride or two to shake legs out.
Lunges.
Big times (stick runs).
Maybe do some drop-jumps and reaction jumps
Faster strides then main session.

I try to get my ankles and achilles working early on as they have given me grief over the years. Our distance groups will do a reduced selection of the above, changing selection a bit each time and won't worry about dorsiflexion and ankle rigidity (switches and pedalling are not relevant for them).

Static stretching - all gentle - I tend to concentrate on the soleus, gastocnemius, hamstrings, hip flexors and shoulders.

As with all things, start with s small quantity of exercises and build up slowly as body allows.

There's two parts, I think.

The skill of running, you don't lose. If you've spent time developing an efficient stride and learned good training methods, you don't completely lose those if you spend a year on the couch.
Your cardio, on the other hand, you can lose that.

There are several things you can do to gain muscle effectively:

Eat enough protein: Protein is essential for muscle growth, as it provides the building blocks your body needs to repair and rebuild muscle tissue. Aim to consume at least 1 gram of protein per pound of body weight each day, and focus on high-quality sources such as lean meats, eggs, dairy products, and plant-based proteins.

Engage in regular strength training: To build muscle, you need to progressively overload your muscles by lifting weights that are heavy enough to challenge them. Aim to include a variety of exercises in your workouts, such as squats, deadlifts, press, and rows, and aim to increase the weight you lift over time as your muscles adapt.
>Don't be a sissy and use the same weights for weeks

Get enough rest: In order for your muscles to grow, you need to give them time to rest and recover between workouts. Aim to get at least 7-9 hours of sleep per night and try to avoid overtraining by allowing for at least one full rest day each week.
>İ sleep Jordan.png

Stay hydrated: Proper hydration is important for muscle growth, as it helps to transport nutrients to your muscles and remove waste products. Aim to drink at least 8-12 cups of water per day, depending on your size and activity level.
>Drink watah budi

Eat enough calories: In order to build muscle, you need to be in a calorie surplus, meaning you need to consume more calories than you burn. Aim to consume enough calories to support your workouts and muscle-building goals, but be mindful not to overdo it, as consuming too many calories can lead a way to

>>69272161
Dietary cholesterol is a fat soluble nutrient.
What is supposedly bad for you according to the mainstream (this is questionable) is high LDL cholesterol. That's a protein that carries several fats and fat soluble nutrients in your bloodstream.
Under certain circumstances LDL can get stuck in your artery walls, which can cause blockages and heart attacks.
Saturated fat can in raise LDL. Dietary cholesterol does not.

That does not mean saturated fat is to be feared. LDL only gets stuck in your artery in specific circumstances, which is when the LDL particle gets damaged and is no longer taken up by the liver. Which causes them to pile up. Which is why LDL particle size is a more important predictor for heart disease than total LDL volume. When a doctor runs your bloodwork they're measuring you total volume, not particle size.

Ironically it's not saturated fat but PUFAs that damage the LDL particle. Exces sugar also plays a role.

I was in the same boat. Fact of the matter is that if you've been fat for a very long time going on a deficit will result in reduced metabolism. There was a study done with biggest loser contestants and they were burning something like 700 calories than they were supposed to.

What I did was take some vacation time and went to a four day long convention. I packed four protein shakes for the day and nothing else, just water from the fountains. I was actively doing shit all day, so I didn't feel the need to eat.

That helped me get to where I could continue to be in a deep caloric deficit and make progress. I also use rest pause lifts. 80% your 1rn for 8-4-2-1 reps with 20 seconds between each. You’re 18; things are going to be fine. I literally didn’t start working out until I was 19 and that’s because I got jumped by my ex’s new BF at the time. Initially, I worked out in pure anger. That works for awhile, but as anyone will tell you, you can’t carry that stuff around forever. The. I’ve had stages in my life I was so depressed that I would stumble into the gym at 6am high because working out was nearly the only thing I was doing right for myself. The, once my life settled down, I actually fell into a good, constant routine and actually made some decent gains. Then i had a kid and lost most of them. Now I’m back at it with renewed purpose.

The point I’m trying to make here is life is full of twists and turns. Me personally, I was accomplishing so much outside of just working out that I didn’t seriously start lifting until I was 30, though I had already been working out on and off for ten years at that point. In that same time I had girlfriends, went from incredibly anxious and awkward to more mellow and self aware, gained confidence in myself, gained and lost friend, went to school, etc. None of these things in my life had to do with lifting in and of itself, but it was just a on and off constant I had in my life if I needed to do something right for my body and mind. Lifting isn’t going to accomplish much on its own, but it does teach you how to stick with and work at something that can be incredibly difficult to do. Just keep building yourself up as a person and you’ll be fine - you have time and don’t get impatient and think this will all happen overnight.

Honestly, if I had your build at 18, I would have been fucking slaying left and right. I was 5’8” and 115 lbs when I was your age. There’s some perspective for you.

>>69273718
There is no such thing as a hypertrophy range that sits neatly between strength and endurance. That is an oversimplification.

There is a gradient of strength and endurance. Anything below 5 reps is mostly strength, anything between 5 and 20 reps has a good mix of both, and anything above 20 is mostly endurance.

Hypertrophy is just a thing that happens when you lift a weight close to failure for volume, regardless of whether your training leans more towards strength or endurance. Hypertrophy has been shown to occur between 5-40 reps so far.

20-40 rep sets are impractical for hypertrophy because they burn too much to be taken to failure by most people. 3 rep sets are impractical for hypertrophy because there’s not enough volume. So many people do 8-12 because they want to grow and don’t want to be in excruciating pain the entire time.

So, your muscles dont really care about numbers. All they need is time under tension or in other words: 10-20 "hard" sets that are close enough to failure. Now I started lifting focusing on the classic compounds and developing my connection with the muscles but these days I just do 1-2 compounds or compound variants for a muscle or muscle group and then some isolations. Some examples: for shoulders I do 4 hard sets of seated DB OHP (rep range anywhere from 6 to 15), some drop set shenanigan lateral raises because they give me a sick pump and 3 to 4 sets of rear delt flys. One big compound, two isolations, 11 or so hard sets total. For legs I do squats, then leg press and then whatever "small" exercise I feel like. If I dont feel like squatting I say fuck it and just go really hard on leg press and vice versa.
Chest is a good example because I do some benching, sometimes flat bb bench, sometimes incline db bench, whatever I feel like. It only matters that its hard enough and gives you a sick pump. Round it off with two more exercises that are more Isolation types.
Idk how to explain but yeah. Hard big movement, burning small movements.
